#' Plot 2D embedding 
#'
#' Plot a 2D representation (embedding) of cells
#' @param embedding_mat Embedding
#' @param colour vector of variable to plot
#' @param randomize Logical. Whether to randomize data before plotting.
#'
#' @return ggplot2 object
#' @export
#'
plot_embedding <- function(embedding_mat,colour,randomize=T, size_point=2) {
  # create a data frame that will have the embedding as well as the colors
  embedding_obj <- data.frame(
    Dim1=embedding_mat[,1],
    Dim2=embedding_mat[,2],
    Var=colour )

  # randomize the order of the objects
  if( randomize ) {
    embedding_obj <- embedding_obj[ sample.int(nrow(embedding_obj)), ]
  }
  # create the plots
  if(is.numeric(colour)) # the color variable is numeric
  {
    #embedding_obj$Var <- embedding_obj$Var - mean(embedding_obj$Var)
    lim <- stats::quantile(abs(embedding_obj$Var),0.99)
    ggplot2::ggplot(
      embedding_obj, ggplot2::aes_string( x="Dim1", y="Dim2", colour="Var"))+
      ggplot2::geom_point(size=size_point)+
      ggplot2::theme_minimal()+
      ggplot2::scale_color_gradientn( limits=c(-lim,lim), colours=c("blue","light grey","red"), oob=scales::squish )
  } else {
    ggplot2::ggplot(
      embedding_obj, ggplot2::aes_string( x="Dim1", y="Dim2", colour="Var"))+
      ggplot2::geom_point(size=size_point)+
      ggplot2::theme_minimal()+
      ggplot2::guides(colour=ggplot2::guide_legend(override.aes=list(size=3)))

  }
}

# Function for cross validation
cv_loo.svm <- function( x, y ) {
  predicted <- c()
  for( i in 1:length(y) ) {
    fit <- svm(x[-i,],y[-i],kernel="linear",probability=T)
    predicted[i] <- attributes(predict(fit,x[i,,drop=F],probability=T))$probabilities[,2]
  }
  return(predicted)
}

Analysis of distortion matrices

First, let's concatenate the distortion matrices of different samples in the proper structuer (one column per sample):

H <- unique(
  cbind(
    meta$shared_donor,
    as.character(meta$group_per_sample),
    meta$cohort) )
rownames(H) <- H[,1]

Q <- NULL
for( i in 1:model$aux$numSamples ) {
  Q <- cbind(Q,c(model$params$Qi[[i]]))
}
colnames(Q) <- model$aux$Samples
rownames(Q) <- paste0( rep(model$aux$geneIDs,model$aux$K), ".Q", rep(1:model$aux$K,each=model$aux$J) )

Now, let's separate the two cohorts, and also remove samples that are probably not suitable (10x reference samples).

H1 <- H[ H[,3]=="cohort1", ]
Q1 <- Q[ , H[,3]=="cohort1" ]
Q1 <- Q1[ , !(H1[,1] %in% c("one_k_v3","Five_k_v3","Ten_k_v3")) ]
H1 <- H1[ !(H1[,1] %in% c("one_k_v3","Five_k_v3","Ten_k_v3")), ]
Q1 <- Q1 - apply(Q1,1,mean)

H2 <- H[ H[,3]=="cohort2", ]
Q2 <- Q[ , H[,3]=="cohort2" ]
Q2 <- Q2 - apply(Q2,1,mean)

smoothScatter(
  apply(Q1,1,sd), apply(Q2,1,sd) )

top_genes <- order( apply(cbind(Q1,Q2),1,sd), decreasing=T )[1:20]
Q1 <- Q1[top_genes,]
Q2 <- Q2[top_genes,]
